vulnerabilities.description: The debug module is vulnerable to regular expression denial of service when untrusted user input is passed into the o formatter. It takes around 50k characters to block for 2 seconds making this a low severity issue. This vulnerability was identified as exploitable by first.org with an EPSS of 0.296%.

analysis.detail: This issue is new, and has not been reviewed yet.

vulnerabilities.description: In jQuery versions greater than or equal to 1.2 and before 3.5.0, passing HTML from untrusted sources - even after sanitizing it - to one of jQuery's DOM manipulation methods (i.e. .html(), .append(), and others) may execute untrusted code. This problem is patched in jQuery 3.5.0. This vulnerability was identified as exploitable by first.org with an EPSS of 6.271%.

analysis.detail: This issue is new, and has not been reviewed yet.

vulnerabilities.description: In jQuery versions greater than or equal to 1.0.3 and before 3.5.0, passing HTML containing <option> elements from untrusted sources - even after sanitizing it - to one of jQuery's DOM manipulation methods (i.e. .html(), .append(), and others) may execute untrusted code. This problem is patched in jQuery 3.5.0. This vulnerability was identified as exploitable by first.org with an EPSS of 2.302%.

analysis.detail: This issue is new, and has not been reviewed yet.

vulnerabilities.description: This affects the package glob-parent before 5.1.2. The enclosure regex used to check for strings ending in enclosure containing path separator. This vulnerability was identified as exploitable by first.org with an EPSS of 1.244%.

analysis.detail: This issue is new, and has not been reviewed yet.

vulnerabilities.description: A vulnerability, which was classified as critical, was found in hughsk flat up to 5.0.0. This affects the function unflatten of the file index.js. The manipulation leads to improperly controlled modification of object prototype attributes ('prototype pollution'). It is possible to initiate the attack remotely. Upgrading to version 5.0.1 is able to address this issue. The name of the patch is 20ef0ef55dfa028caddaedbcb33efbdb04d18e13. It is recommended to upgrade the affected component. The identifier VDB-216777 was assigned to this vulnerability. This vulnerability was identified as exploitable by first.org with an EPSS of 0.726%.

analysis.detail: This issue is new, and has not been reviewed yet.

vulnerabilities.description: minimist before 1.2.2 could be tricked into adding or modifying properties of Object.prototype using a "constructor" or "__proto__" payload. This vulnerability was identified as exploitable by first.org with an EPSS of 0.105%.

analysis.detail: This issue is new, and has not been reviewed yet.

vulnerabilities.description: websocket-extensions ruby module prior to 0.1.5 allows Denial of Service (DoS) via Regex Backtracking. The extension parser may take quadratic time when parsing a header containing an unclosed string parameter value whose content is a repeating two-byte sequence of a backslash and some other character. This could be abused by an attacker to conduct Regex Denial Of Service (ReDoS) on a single-threaded server by providing a malicious payload with the Sec-WebSocket-Extensions header. This vulnerability was identified as exploitable by first.org with an EPSS of 1.647%.

analysis.detail: This issue is new, and has not been reviewed yet.

vulnerabilities.description: Due to unbounded alias chasing, a maliciously crafted YAML file can cause the system to consume significant system resources. If parsing user input, this may be used as a denial of service vector.

analysis.detail: This issue is new, and has not been reviewed yet.

vulnerabilities.description: Minimist <=1.2.5 is vulnerable to Prototype Pollution via file index.js, function setKey() (lines 69-95). This vulnerability was identified as exploitable by first.org with an EPSS of 3.488%.

analysis.detail: This issue is new, and has not been reviewed yet.

vulnerabilities.description: This affects versions of the package http-cache-semantics before 4.1.1. The issue can be exploited via malicious request header values sent to a server, when that server reads the cache policy from the request using this library. This vulnerability was identified as exploitable by first.org with an EPSS of 0.194%.

analysis.detail: This issue is new, and has not been reviewed yet.

vulnerabilities.description: Versions of the package semver before 7.5.2 are vulnerable to Regular Expression Denial of Service (ReDoS) via the function new Range, when untrusted user data is provided as a range. This vulnerability was identified as exploitable by first.org with an EPSS of 0.227%.

analysis.detail: This issue is new, and has not been reviewed yet.

vulnerabilities.description: Parsing malicious or large YAML documents can consume excessive amounts of CPU or memory. This vulnerability was identified as exploitable by first.org with an EPSS of 0.719%.

analysis.detail: This issue is new, and has not been reviewed yet.

vulnerabilities.description: The got package before 12.1.0 (also fixed in 11.8.5) for Node.js allows a redirect to a UNIX socket.

analysis.detail: This issue is new, and has not been reviewed yet.

vulnerabilities.description: A vulnerability was found in the minimatch package. This flaw allows a Regular Expression Denial of Service (ReDoS) when calling the braceExpand function with specific arguments, resulting in a Denial of Service. This vulnerability was identified as exploitable by first.org with an EPSS of 0.179%.

analysis.detail: This issue is new, and has not been reviewed yet.

vulnerabilities.description: xml2js version 0.4.23 allows an external attacker to edit or add new properties to an object. This is possible because the application does not properly validate incoming JSON keys, thus allowing the __proto__ property to be edited. This vulnerability was identified as exploitable by first.org with an EPSS of 0.101%.

analysis.detail: This issue is new, and has not been reviewed yet.

vulnerabilities.description: The ip package before 1.1.9 for Node.js might allow SSRF because some IP addresses (such as 0x7f.1) are improperly categorized as globally routable via isPublic.

analysis.detail: This issue is new, and has not been reviewed yet.

vulnerabilities.description: node-tar is a Tar for Node.js. node-tar prior to version 6.2.1 has no limit on the number of sub-folders created in the folder creation process. An attacker who generates a large number of sub-folders can consume memory on the system running node-tar and even crash the Node.js client within few seconds of running it using a path with too many sub-folders inside. Version 6.2.1 fixes this issue by preventing extraction in excessively deep sub-folders.

analysis.detail: This issue is new, and has not been reviewed yet.

vulnerabilities.description: The ip package through 2.0.1 for Node.js might allow SSRF because some IP addresses (such as 127.1, 01200034567, 012.1.2.3, 000:0:0000::01, and ::fFFf:127.0.0.1) are improperly categorized as globally routable via isPublic. NOTE: this issue exists because of an incomplete fix for CVE-2023-42282.

analysis.detail: This issue is new, and has not been reviewed yet.

vulnerabilities.description: The NPM package `micromatch` prior to 4.0.8 is vulnerable to Regular Expression Denial of Service (ReDoS). The vulnerability occurs in `micromatch.braces()` in `index.js` because the pattern `.*` will greedily match anything. By passing a malicious payload, the pattern matching will keep backtracking to the input while it doesn't find the closing bracket. As the input size increases, the consumption time will also increase until it causes the application to hang or slow down. There was a merged fix but further testing shows the issue persists. This issue should be mitigated by using a safe pattern that won't start backtracking the regular expression due to greedy matching. This issue was fixed in version 4.0.8.

analysis.detail: This issue is new, and has not been reviewed yet.

vulnerabilities.description: The NPM package `braces`, versions prior to 3.0.3, fails to limit the number of characters it can handle, which could lead to Memory Exhaustion. In `lib/parse.js,` if a malicious user sends "imbalanced braces" as input, the parsing will enter a loop, which will cause the program to start allocating heap memory without freeing it at any moment of the loop. Eventually, the JavaScript heap limit is reached, and the program will crash.

analysis.detail: This issue is new, and has not been reviewed yet.
